ce:section.ce:para:
A practical application of the proposed strategy was evaluated by sensing sparfloxacin in human serum samples. Sparfloxacin (0.1, 0.2, and 0.4 μg/mL) were spiked into the serum samples (Table 1
                        ). The amount of sparfloxacin recovered was 88.8%–102%, and the relative standard deviations were less than 5%. These results indicated that the new sensing materials have great potential in the direct determination of sparfloxacin in actual serum samples. Several methods have been reported in the literature for the detection of sparfloxacin in real samples, and their key performances are summarized in Table 2
                        . Table 2 shows the level of analytical performance achieved with this method. The detection limit and linear range of this method are comparable or superior to those obtained by previous works. Moreover, this method has been successfully used to detect real human serum samples with satisfactory recoveries.
